<div id="review_1913911912" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1913911912" />
    <a title="Isen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32668223-isen"><img alt="Isen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509360819p2/32668223.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1913911912?book_show_action=true">Feb 19, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Isen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Isen" href="/user/show/32668223-isen">Isen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1913911912" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9472164083606580885">The book consists of three essays written by a Zen priest as advice to a martial artist. The first essay&apos;s input can be summarised as &quot;don&apos;t focus on the opponent&apos;s sword&quot;. A valid point, to be sure, but one that could be stated much more succinctly. The other two, from what I can tell, have very little to do with martial arts at all, but just ruminations on Buddhism and Zen in particular. I can only assume that the arguments therein are very profound to a practitioner, as to a layman they are a</span>
  <span id="freeText9472164083606580885" style="display:none">The book consists of three essays written by a Zen priest as advice to a martial artist. The first essay's input can be summarised as "don't focus on the opponent's sword". A valid point, to be sure, but one that could be stated much more succinctly. The other two, from what I can tell, have very little to do with martial arts at all, but just ruminations on Buddhism and Zen in particular. I can only assume that the arguments therein are very profound to a practitioner, as to a layman they are at best vacuous, and more often meaningless.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9472164083606580885" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
