        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2943106135" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18030733873727097652">I liked the book. It has interesting insights on the sentience and immanence of beings. Takuan also talks about how the martial artist should always maintain a state of &quot;flowing&quot; or &quot;no-mind&quot;, avoiding interruption or setting the mind on something, since this fraction of hesitation can cost his life in a bout. This is way easier said than done; for that reason, this is not a book to be read in a hurry. It takes a life of practicing these principles. Since they are writings from a zen master to a</span>
  <span id="freeText18030733873727097652" style="display:none">I liked the book. It has interesting insights on the sentience and immanence of beings. Takuan also talks about how the martial artist should always maintain a state of "flowing" or "no-mind", avoiding interruption or setting the mind on something, since this fraction of hesitation can cost his life in a bout. This is way easier said than done; for that reason, this is not a book to be read in a hurry. It takes a life of practicing these principles. Since they are writings from a zen master to a master swordsman (Yagyū Munenori), one cannot expect the teachings to be anything near practical.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18030733873727097652" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
